The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems, which are typically studied in the subfield of computer science known as "Discrete Mathematics and Combinatorial Optimization" (cs.DM). The paper also discusses the use of linear programming to model these problems, which is a common technique in the subfield of "Computational Complexity" (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper provides refutations for claims made in recent literature, which suggests that it may fall under the subfield of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG) or "Numerical Analysis" (cs.NE).
